<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-206-138  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 206 138.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  April 25 1989 n1163* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Objectives of new Object Management Group brings new threat toproprietary environments. (Object Management Group)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hewlett-Packard Co. (marketing).andO;Ticker:    HWP.andO;Product:   NewWave (Graphical user interface) (marketing).andO;Topic:     Trade and Professional AssociationsObject-Oriented LanguagesPromotion of ProductStandardizationObject Management GroupGoals and Objectives.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>OBJECTIVES OF NEW OBJECT MANAGEMENT GROUP BRING NEW THREATandM;TO PROPRIETARY ENVIRONMENTSandM;The new Object Management Group that has coalesced aroundandM;Hewlett-Packard Co's NewWave environment (CI No 1,160) has the declared aimof making computer systems and software from different manufacturers work andcommunicate together more efficiently.andP;  Object-oriented programming is solittle understood that we can't have too many definitions, and the ObjectManagers say that an object-oriented environment treats different types ofdata and applications like building blocks that can be mixed across operatingsystems to create complex applications quickly and easily - to which one canadd that, once defined, objects are usable by programmers without the need tounderstand their internal structure in any detail.andP;  The executive director ofthe group is Data General Corp's Christopher Stone, who believes that objectmanagement will be &quot;the next significant breakthrough in applicationenvironments&quot;.andP;  &quot;We shall adopt and support a core of commercially availableimplementations, actively influence their acceptance and development, andestablish a mechanism for certifying that these implementations comply withthe core technology,&quot; he says.andP;  The objectives of the Object Managers includethe promotion of an object-oriented applications- integration environmentbased on appropriate industry standards; promotion of a framework forcompatible and independent development of applications; making possibleco-ordination among applications across heterogeneous networked systems in amultinational, multilingual environment; adoption of a core of commerciallyavailable implementations of the framework and promotion of theirinternational market acceptance and use; the active influence of the futuredirection and development of the core products and technologies; fostering ofthe development of tools and applications that conform to and extend theframework, and providing a mechanism for certifying compliance with the coretechnology; and adoption of the Hewlett-Packard NewWave object managementfacility, independent of user interface, as a working example of theframework.andP;  Each of the 11 founder members is committed to active research ordevelopment of products based on the common applications environment.andP;  Itwill be interesting to  see who else decides to join the Object Group, whichposes another threat to companies committed to proprietary environments.andO;</TEXT></DOC>